I don&#39;t quite follow the part where you try to determine the separation. In Go, like in C, you can do arithmetic on characters. For example, you&#39;ll get the 0-based index of each lower-case letter with:

    pos := char - &#39;a&#39;;

You can the turn `&quot;abxyz&quot;` to

    {0, 1, 23, 24, 25}.

If you take the difference between adjacent letters, you&#39;ll get

    {-25, 1, 22, 1, 1}

(-25 ist the difference between the last and the first value.) You have two gaps: One where your cycle begins between b and w and another one where the alphabet wraps. The second gap is where the difference is negative, always between the last and first items. You can add 26 to the difference to adjust it or you can use modular arithmetic, where you use the remainder `%` to account for the wrapping:

    diff := ((p - q + 26) % 26;

The `%` forces the result to the range from 0 to 25 if the first operand is positive. The + 26 enforces that it is positive. (The program below uses 25, because your definition of separation is not the difference in position, but the number of lterres in between.)

Now you have the differences

    {1, 1, 22, 1, 1}

When you have only at most two dfferent values and one of them occurs at most once, your condition is met. (That&#39;s a condition which I find surprisingly complicated to test, see below, but part of that is because Go&#39;s map is a bit cumbersome.)

Anyway, here&#39;s the code:

    package main
    
    import &quot;fmt&quot;
    
    func list(str string) int {
    	present := [26]bool{}
    	pos := []int{}
    
    	count := map[int]int{}
    
    	// determine which letters exist
    	for _, c := range str {
    		if &#39;a&#39; &lt;= c &amp;&amp; c &lt;= &#39;z&#39; {
    			present[c-&#39;a&#39;] = true
    		}
    	}
    
    	// concatenate all used letters (count sort, kinda)
    	for i := 0; i &lt; 26; i++ {
    		if present[i] {
    			pos = append(pos, i)
    		}
    	}
    
    	// find differences
    	q := pos[len(pos)-1]
    	for _, p := range pos {
    		diff := (p - q + 25) % 26
    
    		count[diff]++
    		q = p
    	}
    
    	// check whether input is a &quot;rambai&quot;
    	if len(count) &gt; 2 {
    		return -1
    	}
    
    	which := []int{}
    	occur := []int{}
    	for k, v := range count {
    		which = append(which, k)
    		occur = append(occur, v)
    	}
    
    	if len(which) &lt; 2 {
    		return which[0]
    	}
    
    	if occur[0] != 1 &amp;&amp; occur[1] != 1 {
    		return -1
    	}
    
    	if occur[0] == 1 {
    		return which[1]
    	}
    
    	return which[0]
    }
    
    func testme(str string) {
    	fmt.Printf(&quot;\&quot;%s\&quot;: %d\n&quot;, str, list(str))
    }
    
    func main() {
    	testme(&quot;zzzzyyyybbbzzzaaaaaxxx&quot;)
    	testme(&quot;yacegw&quot;)
    	testme(&quot;keebeebheeh&quot;)
    	testme(&quot;aco&quot;)
    	testme(&quot;naan&quot;)
    	testme(&quot;mississippi&quot;)
    	testme(&quot;rosemary&quot;)
    }

